Lab 2 – Problem Solving and Python Coding
(70 Points)
In this lab, we will learn how to write simple Python programs to get familiar with Python syntax.
Lab Deliverable:
You need to deliver a single doc/docx/pdf file that contains:
1. Your name, Lab #
2. Screen shots to show all your work in Parts I, II and III. If you are using another IDE, make sure
that you show your code and the obtained output.
Getting started for writing the Python code:
• First, open IDLE. In the top menu, select File -> New
• Save the new file with any name.
• Write the code for your program in that file.
• Save the file.
• Run your code by pressing F5, or by going to the above menu and selecting Run -> Run Module.
• When your program runs, it will take you to the main Python console.
• On the python console, you need to input the values needed by the program.
• The output/result of the program should be printed.
Problem 1: (30 points)
a) Write a program to add 2 numbers.
b) Write a program to swap 2 variable values.
c) Write a Python program to compute the perimeter and area of a rectangle.
Problem 2: (40 points)
a) Write a program to find the circumference and area of a circle.
b) Write a program that converts temperatures from Fahrenheit to Celsius
c) Write a program to solve a given quadratic equation. e.g. a = 1, b = 3, c = 4
Hint:
• You may have to import the math library in case you plan to use sqrt
d) Write a program to determine the compound interest. Given the principal amount
(5000 dollars) and the annual percent interest rate (APR) as 3%, the program should be able to
calculate the value of the investment 10 years into the future.
Amount = Principal * (1 + APR/100)
